Back in 2020, a team of researchers successfully piloted a 22.5 kg and 3 m wide scale model of the Flying-V back. Takeoff of the aircraft was easily performed at a speed of 80km/h.

node.text:
The Pentagon is reportedly experimenting with AI and other cutting edge technology in the hope of being able to ‘predict the future’.

The experiment known as Global Information Dominance Experiments (GIDE) uses AI and other technology used in the experiments could offer the Pentagon a strong ‘ability to see days in advance’.

The machine learning-based AI will observe changes in raw, real-time data that hint at possible trouble. For example, if satellite imagery shows signs that a rival nation's submarine are preparing to leave port, the AI could flag that mobilization knowing the vessel will likely leave soon.

Military analysts can take hours or even days to comb through this information. However, GIDE technology could send an alert within seconds according to Pentagon officials.

Due to technological advancements such as the GIDE, any future conflicts could end up being won on the basis of who has the strongest AI. Battlefields could even end up being won by technological devices rather than people, as artificial intelligence systems can make decisions far faster than any human can.

The car weighs 360kg and can fly at a maximum speed of 130km/h. The X2 comes equipped with autonomous flight path planning capabilities. It can monitor the ground using its multiple sensors and also gets self-help return to land.

The flying car also has a safety design onboard such as eight independent battery groups for redundant power supply as well as four axes and eight propellers for multi-motor power backup. It also gets an ejection parachute and 24-hour monitoring system.

Are we finally entering the era of flying cars?

node.text:
Dubai police will be able to respond to an incident anywhere in the United Arab Emirates city within a minute, thanks to a network of pre-positioned drone bases.

The quadcopters, supplied by Israeli company Airobotics, will operate from base stations during the Expo 2020 event starting in October this year, an exhibition said to be the third-largest event in the world after the Olympics and the World Cup.

The drones will reduce police response time from 4.4 minutes to 1 minute according to a tweet from Dubai’s ruler Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum.

Each base has a sliding roof that allows the drones to enter and exit. The drones can fly pre-programmed patrols, or be dispatched to a specific location, allowing an operator at police headquarters to inspect the scene, or follow a suspicious individual or vehicle and pass data to other police units.
